{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":913,"record_hash":"sha256:c30bcfebe65c13d151b452c53b3b9fc175fa0ad3e0cd162d9b0cef6cfa0767b1","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:11:36.270Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 87e2ea\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1131\nOutput:\n# Session Association Strategy\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> This is historical background, not the active implementation plan. The current\n> direction is [Including Turns In Agentlog](Including-turns.md).\n\nThis note captures the association lessons that still matter after the move to\nturn-based capture.\n\nThe old strategy explored explicit attach, commit-time confirmation, review\npickers, active session pins, change-id links, commit SHA links, and\nevidence-based recomputation. That comparison was useful, but the active plan is\nnow simpler:\n\n```text\ncapture observations -> write derived lookup indexes -> score associations on read\n```\n\nV1 should not require a human confirmation step. It also should not automatically\npersist inferred relationships as durable truth. Capture records facts. Read\npaths derive likely related sessions with confidence labels and reasons.\n\n## Current Direction\n\n- Keep the durable transcript object project-scoped:\n\n  ```text\n  project\n    gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:*\n  ```\n\n- Add capture turns under each session:\n\n  ```text\n  one session -> many capture turns -> many transcript records\n  ```\n\n- Store environment observations on each turn: worktree files, stacks, branches,\n  review identifiers, change ids, commit ids, and path-only commit file lists.\n- Write derived lookup indexes for branch, review, and change candidates.\n- Do not write a path index in v1.\n- Compute association results at read time from indexed candidates plus turn\n  details.\n- Show high-confidence related sessions automatically, with reasons.\n- Phrase results as \"likely related session evidence\", not provenance proof.\n\n## Durable Links\n\nThe existing explicit relationship shape may still exist:\n\n```text\n<target>\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nIf present, these explicit links should be treated as strong evidence. They are\nnot the default v1 association mechanism.\n\nFuture product/API flows may add dura\n[TRUNCATED]\nt operations can bypass GitButler metadata lifecycle hooks\n\nFalse positives are worse than missed links because they can mislead reviewers\nabout how code was produced.\n\nCapture should therefore write observations and indexes, not final inferred\nownership claims.\n\n## Useful Signals\n\nThe active scoring model lives in\n[Including Turns In Agentlog](Including-turns.md), but the important signal\nordering is:\n\n- direct explicit links, if present, are strongest\n- previous-turn worktree files later appearing in observed commit file lists is\n  strong evidence\n- directly observed change ids, review ids, or pull request ids are strong\n  candidate evidence\n- branch-name observation is useful but weak by itself\n- repeated observation strengthens a session-level result\n- broad/truncated file lists, many visible branches, and failed environment\n  snapshots weaken confidence\n\n## Lifecycle Risks\n\nDurable relationships, if added later, still have lifecycle risks:\n\n- amend can add new relevant turns to an existing change\n- uncommit/recommit can orphan or blur links\n- split or move operations can divide evidence across destinations\n- squash can merge several evidence sources into one surviving change\n- reorder/rebase changes commit ids\n- branch rename/delete/recreate can make branch-level links stale\n- undo/redo can replay stale metadata\n- plain Git operations can bypass relationship maintenance\n\nThat lifecycle footprint is the main reason v1 prefers derived read-time\nassociation results over persisted inferred links.\n\n## Change IDs\n\nChange ids remain the best future code-level anchor, but they are not magic:\n\n- synthetic change ids derived from commit ids are not durable across rewrites\n- squash may keep one surviving change id and drop others\n- uncommit/recommit can break continuity unless GitButler preserves identity\n- plain Git operations can bypass GitButler's ability to maintain links\n\nFor v1, change ids are useful association evidence and index keys. They are not\nthe basis for automatic durable relationship propagation.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:11:36.270Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}